getPRISMTemps

Jon Downs

2022-08-07

How to get a year of daily census tract level temperature data in 118 lines of R code.

Introduction


For a recent project, I was interested in temperature-level data at the census tract level. After some sleuthing, I learned that one of the best data sources may be from the PRISM Climate Group at Oregon State. The only problem was, I needed data in tabular format, but it seems they only have it in raster format. I was able to write a simple yet powerful R script that can download a years worth of daily temperature data and convert them to CSV files with tract-level max temperature data for the state of Washington. And I will show you how! This article will walk through how to:


  1. Download multiple .zip files
  2. Unzip multiple .zip files
  3. Use parallel processing in R
  4. Convert raster data into CSV
    1. Bonus: Ill even explain what raster data are!


And, at the end, I will put it all together in a single script that you can use to download an entire year of temperature data. Though, fair warning, you might not want to do it on a laptop.


Getting set up


First, I encourage you to click on that link above and read a bit about the PRISM Climate Group. Heck, you may even want to engage with their citizen science program. Eventually, you might find your way to their FTP site. Before we download the data though, lets get our R session set up properly:


# Load libraries
library(jsonlite)
library(rvest)
library(raster)
library(rgdal)
library(sp)
library(tidyverse)
library(parallel)

# Set Year and batch size
year <- 2011
n_ras_to_csv <- 20

# Set up parallel runs (save 2 cores)
nc <- detectCores() - 2
cl <- makeCluster(nc)

# Load configuration settings (using hidden environmental variable)
# TO USE: make a .JSON file a variable called dirPRISM where all this data
#         will be stored
cfig_file <- paste0(Sys.getenv('myrconfig'), 'extractPRISM.json')
config <- jsonlite::read_json(cfig_file)

# Path to where all BIL files will download (make if necessary)
bil_dir <- paste0(config$dirPRISM, 'TMAX/BIL/')
dir.create(bil_dir, recursive = TRUE)

# Create a download directory for year TMAX data (make if necessary)
download_dir <- paste0(bil_dir, year, '/')
dir.create(download_dir)

# Where our final CSV files will go
csv_dir <- paste0(config$dirPRISM, 'TMAX/CSV/', year, '/')
dir.create(csv_dir, recursive = TRUE)

tract10_fn <- paste0(config$tract10dir, "tract10.shp")


Lets walk through all of that. First, we load rvest, the tidyverse, and other libraries we will be using. Then, we set the year of data we want and how many raster files we want to convert at each run. We are doing this because the part that turns a raster file into CSV data is pretty power hungry. For the same reason, we will want to set up parallel processing. A full explanation of parallel processing is a topic for another post. Briefly, parallel processing lets us run code faster than we normally would by spreading it across multiple cores. In this example, we are saving two cores. Usually, its wise to save a couple of cores for other, non-R related things.


Then, before I get to the work part of the script, I also wanted to specify some directories. Namely, where I will download data and where I will save the final CSV versions of the data. To help keep my code organized and portable, I like to use a JSON file as a config file. A config file is where one would store any variables that would need to be updated if someone wanted to run your script on their machine. The config file says Hey, change these bits, then this will work for you!. I also did a final, perhaps-over-the-top step where I stored even the path to my config files in an environmental variable. I really would quite prefer it if you did not know how I organized my PC, if its all the same to you. But, I digress. My config file looks like this:


{
  "dirPRISM": "C:/YOUR/FILE/PATH/HERE/",
  "tract10dir":  "Z:/NONE/OF/YOUR/BUSINESS/"
}


Those two directories are 1) the main directory where you want all the PRISM data (raw and transformed) as well as the directory for your census tract data file (more on that in a minute). From there, the script names and creates the sub-directories needed to run the script.


Download some data!


Now for some fun! We are going to be downloading a bil file. A bil is a type of raster file, or a rectangular array of regularly spaced pixels. In practice, a raster file is a combination of an image that is color-coded by some variable and a metadata file that explains the values associated with each color. The below chunk of code will download the bil files for an ENTIRE YEAR at once. It will take a couple of minutes. A few of the downloads will likely fail. This is okay: the script will be ran multiple times, and we programmed it in such a way that any stragglers will be re-attempted on the next run of the script. The code:


# DOWNLOAD FILES ----------------------------------------------------------
# List all of the PRISM files on an FTP site
listPRISMFiles <- function(var, year){
  var <- tolower(var)
  lnk <- glue::glue("https://ftp.prism.oregonstate.edu/daily/{var}/{year}")
  ftp_txt <- read_html(lnk)
  ftp_files <- html_attr(html_nodes(ftp_txt, 'a'), 'href')
  ftp_files <- ftp_files[grepl('PRISM', ftp_files)]
  return(list(lnk = lnk, files = ftp_files))
}

# Get TMAX files for year
files <- listPRISMFiles(var = 'tmax', year = year)

# Check for already downloaded files (we don't want to download twice)
already_downloaded <- list.files(download_dir, pattern = '.zip')
files$files <- files$files[!(files$files %in% already_downloaded)]

# Download all of the files specified
dlPRISMDaily <- function(baselnk, file, outdir){
  fn <- paste0(baselnk, '/', file)
  download.file(fn, destfile = paste0(outdir, file))
}
dlPRISMDaily(baselnk = files$lnk, file = files$files, outdir = download_dir)


Here, we start by writing a function, listPRISMfiles. Here, we specify the variable we are interested in (using PRISM nomenclature) as well as the year of data we want to download. I want max temperature (TMAX) data. From there, the function will populate a string with the path to the FTP site containing all of the files for the user-specified year. Then, it will navigate to that page, identify all of the hyperlinks from the page, and keep the ones that look like links to the data files (all of the data files contain the phrase PRISM). The function will return two things: 1) the base name of the hyperlink for all of the files 2) a list of files available at the base link. After we write the function, we run it and store its results in the files variable. These are the files we might want to download. But remember, we plan on running this script more than once. So, we add a step where we look for any .zip files that weve already downloaded. If we find some, we exclude them so that we dont double-download the data. If there is nothing to download, the script will throw a soft warning about a non-zero exit status.


Download some data!


Next, lets unzip all of the data we just downloaded. We will look for any files with the .zip pattern in our download folder. Again, we need to account for the fact that this script may be ran more than once. This is why were not just using one of the variables from above. Here, we wrote a quick helper function to unzip the files with the same name as the originally downloaded file (minus the .zip).

# UNZIP FILES -------------------------------------------------------------
# Identify all of the .zip files in the directory we just created
unzip_fns <- list.files(download_dir, pattern = ".zip")

# Identify already-unzipped versions of these files, remove from list
already_unzipped <- basename(list.dirs(download_dir))
unzip_fns <- unzip_fns[!(gsub('.zip', '', unzip_fns) %in% already_unzipped)]

# Unzip the files that need it
lapply(unzip_fns, function(x) 
  unzip(paste0(download_dir, x), 
        exdir = paste0(download_dir, '/', gsub(".zip", '', x))))


Explore the data!


Okay, we have some data! Now, lets read it in and take a peek.


# Identify the first .bil file
myBilFile <- list.files(download_dir, pattern = '.bil$', recursive = TRUE)[1]
myRast <- raster::raster(paste0(download_dir, myBilFile)[[1]])
plot(myRast)


Voila! A color-coded heat map of max US temperatures on 1/1/2011. But we may need this data in tabular form for, say, a model. So, how do we take this picture, break it up into geographic areas, and get the average max temperature for the day? The answer is actually quite simple. We just need to find a shapefile that has the boundaries we want then use the extract function from raster to get the mean value for all points within each geography. Lets start by getting a shapefile and plotting it along with our raster file. We will use the Washington Office of Financial Managements (OFM) files. Download those files, unzip them, and point to them with the tract10dir variable in your configuration file. Next, lets take a look at the shapefile overlayed on our raster image. We will need to make sure that the shapefile and the raster are in the same projection system first:


# Read in shapefile, convert to new CRS
waCensus10 <- readOGR(tract10_fn)
## Warning in OGRSpatialRef(dsn, layer, morphFromESRI = morphFromESRI,
## dumpSRS = dumpSRS, : Discarded datum NAD83_High_Accuracy_Reference_Network
## in Proj4 definition: +proj=lcc +lat_0=45.3333333333333 +lon_0=-120.5
## +lat_1=45.8333333333333 +lat_2=47.3333333333333 +x_0=500000 +y_0=0 +ellps=GRS80
## +units=us-ft +no_defs
## OGR data source with driver: ESRI Shapefile 
## Source: "D:\PRISM\tract10\tract10.shp", layer: "tract10"
## with 1458 features
## It has 34 fields
## Integer64 fields read as strings:  ALANDM AWATERM
shp_reproj <- spTransform(waCensus10, crs(myRast))

# Plot raster and overlay shapefile
plot(myRast)
plot(shp_reproj, bg = 'transparent', add = TRUE)


Looks accurate, we are almost ready to extract! One problem: the raster (background image) is so much larger than our census tract borders (shapefile). Its not a problem, per se, except that our final step will go much faster if we dont use the whole raster image. Lets fix that using the crop function. Crop works just like it would in MS Paint: it takes a subset of a larger image. Code:

# Subset the raster image to speed things up
myRast2 <- crop(myRast, shp_reproj)
plot(myRast2)
plot(shp_reproj, bg = 'transparent', add = TRUE)

# Get mean temp across each boundary
myExtract <- raster::extract(myRast2, shp_reproj, fun = mean)

# Put in dataframe format, add date and tract identifiers
myOutputData <- data.frame('GEOID10' = shp_reproj@data$GEOID10, 
                           date = as.Date('2011-01-01'), 
                           TMAX = myExtract)

# Take a peek at the data
head(myOutputData)
